[2] Italy (Sardinia)
Date: Fri 23 Nov 2012
Source: Istituto Zooprofilattico Sperimentale G Pegreffi, Sassari, Sardinia [in Italian, machine trans., summ. & edited]
http://www.izs-sardegna.it/primopiano.cfm?id=677


Schmallenberg virus: 1st case isolated in Sardinia
--------------------------------------------------
The 1st case of the new ruminant pathogen Schmallenberg virus (SBV), initially isolated in 2011 in Germany, has been reported in Sardinia. The confirmation of the outbreak came from the Reference Centre for Exotic Diseases (CESME) of Teramo, where laboratory tests were applied on samples sent by the Istituto Zooprofilattico of Sardinia (Animal Health Institute; IZS). The initial clinical and anatomopathological investigations were carried out in a sheep flock in Tertenia in Ogliastra [province].

The IZS has been contacted by the attending veterinarian who observed some cases of abortion in sheep and foeti malformations. Suspicion of SBV was raised, the local and regional health authorities alerted.

Following the confirmation of SBV, some protective measures, prescribed by health protocols, have been undertaken, including entomological surveillance. Ongoing monitoring for bluetongue (BT; similarly transmitted by _Culicoides_), on the other hand, had already demonstrated wide BT dissemination in Ogliastra, favored by high temperatures at the end of November [see ProMED-mail posting 20121026.1367567].

SBV was isolated for the 1st time in the late summer of 2011 in the German town of the same name, in North Rhine-Westphalia, from which it derived its name. Although some symptoms of SBV are similar and comparable to those of other diseases, the analysis of the genome has established that it is a new disease, the presence of which, after its 1st identification, was confirmed in most European countries, including Italy, Denmark, and Belgium. In our Peninsula, the 1st case was registered in February 2012 in the Province of Treviso, followed by new episodes totalling 9 confirmed outbreaks.

The probability of SBV transmission from animals to humans is extremely low, if at all.

--
Communicated by:
Gert van der Hoek
Senior Moderator
